  "response_text": "Here's a practical approach:\n\n**Best budget options for fiber:**\n- Dried beans (black, pinto, kidney) - ~7g fiber per cooked cup, very cheap\n- Lentils - ~8g per cooked cup, quick-cooking\n- Oats - ~8g per cup dry, versatile\n- Brown rice - ~3.5g per cooked cup\n- Whole wheat flour - if you bake your own bread\n\n**Realistic daily strategy:**\n- 1 cup cooked beans/lentils (7-8g)\n- 1 cup oatmeal (8g)\n- 2 slices whole grain bread (4-6g)\n- Gets you to ~20-25g fairly easily\n\n**Practical tips:**\n- Buy in bulk from bins or ethnic markets (often cheaper)\n- Cook large batches and freeze portions\n- Mix grains/legumes together for complete proteins and better taste\n- Start fiber increases gradually to avoid digestive issues\n- Drink plenty of water—fiber needs it to work\n\n**Honest limitation:**\nYou'll probably need *some* variety to stick with it (vegetables add fiber too and aren't always expensive—seasonal produce, frozen, canned). Pure grain/legume diets get monotonous fast.\n\nWhat's your current fiber intake? That affects how aggressively you should increase it.",
